Georgia has an educated population, with a high gradation rate: 93 percent of all Georgians who began their educational process at 8 years old have a high school degree and 27 percent graduated university, she said.

A particularly bright part of the program was the viewing of a travel video from Georgia, produced by Chamber member Rob Joslyn. Joslyn, who has created other videos for the group, leads groups to his home country twice a year.

This year's tours to Georgia attracted almost 50 people -- "which just confirms the huge interest to the country," Kapnisis said. The group passed through Azerbaijan, Armenia and Georgia.

The last day of the trip included a get-together of the Georgian Diaspora, which bring together the people from the Democratic Republic of Georgia who live in the U.S.

"One of my personal favorite parts is the event of the Georgian Diaspora at Chateau Elan winery," Kapnisis said. "We can meet there with people from other cities. We can meet and greet and bond again for the coming years."
